Cedar Anthony Walton, Jr. (January 17, 1934 – August 19, 2013) was an American hard bop jazz pianist.
Walton was born and grew up in Dallas, Texas.
Walton cited Nat King Cole, Bud Powell, Thelonious Monk and Art Tatum as his major influences on piano.
Walton was tempted by the promise of New York City through his associations with John Coltrane, Charlie Parker, and Richie Powell, whom he met at after-hours sessions around Denver, Colorado.
Walton was drafted into the U.S. Army and stationed in Germany, cutting short his rising status in the after-hours jazz scene.

In the early 1960s Walton joined Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers as a pianist-arranger (on the same day Freddie Hubbard joined the group), where, for the next three years, he wrote and arranged such originals as "Ugetsu" and "Mosaic".
Many of Walton's compositions have become jazz standards, including "Firm Roots", "Bolivia" (perhaps his best known), "Holy Land", "Mode for Joe" and "Cedar's Blues".
In January 2010, Walton was inducted as a National Endowment for the Arts Jazz Master.
Walton played and recorded with drummer Billy Higgins from the mid-1960s through the 1990s.
